The KFCB has the unenviable task of defining what “clean content” entails for the nation and a film like Rafiki was simply collateral damage.Policing morality in films could end up being counterproductive by stifling creativity in the name of sanitising and regulating content What qualifies as clean content?
Here’s a hint: “It must not have a homosexual theme and clear intent to promote lesbianism in Kenya contrary to the law.”
This is the reason the Kenya Film Classification Board (KFCB) gave in 2018 for banning the film Rafiki. Before the ban, the Board had asked Wanuri Kahiu, the director, to change the ending, which was deemed “too hopeful and positive”. She refused. Good for her for refusing to bow to the demands of “clean content”.



