The KFCB has the unenviable task of defining what “clean content” entails for the nation and a film like Rafiki was simply collateral damage. The Board has been on a long, arduous journey of ridding the airwaves of “dirty” content, going as far as appointing clean content ambassadors, announcing that through them, “the Board hopes to reach every corner of the nation and affect every sphere and field with our ‘Clean is Cool’ message.”





In the just-concluded Kisima Awards, KFCB awarded Sh1 million to Zamaradi Productions for the clean content in their film Dream Child. Dream Child is a flick about “a teenager called Kevin, who finds himself trapped between a cruel society and a seemingly kind but dark world”. KFCB announced that the film was awarded for its compliance with the requirements of the (Film and Stage Plays Act) Cap 222.
This sets a dangerous precedent. It would be interesting to read the judges’ remarks on how the marks for morality were awarded and what disqualified other films from scooping the award.
Monetary value
There’s something disturbing about attaching monetary value to morality, even if it’s meant as positive reinforcement. Shouldn’t morality be a bare minimum requirement for any film entered in the awards, especially since we know that X-rated movies will always stick to their lanes?



