“Moral Cop” Dr Ezekiel Mutua’s efforts to prescribe what’s moral have always attracted praise and criticism in equal measure. It has also not escaped the nation’s attention that the rebukes have sometimes felt like religious sermons.
Policing morality in films could end up being counterproductive by stifling creativity in the name of sanitising and regulating content. Case in point, Rafiki.
In the wake of teenagers gone rogue in this Covid-19 period, and in the spirit of art being a reflection of society, an award for “cleanliness in content” could encourage the society to bury its head deeper in the sand on matters sex, drugs abuse and teenage pregnancies, which should be faced head-on.
The guidelines on sex, obscenity and pornography are quite clear in the programming code for free-to-air radio and television services in Kenya, so this is not a call to contravene this but to have open, artistic expression, minus the morality tag.
Monetary compensation for morality seems rather fraudulent, like an invitation — even pressure —for creatives to conform to a moral code that’s only evident to KFCB.
